Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Court calls 16CM65 & 16CM132 @ 9:13 am. Defendant Jeremy J. Gasser in court with attorney Gavin Grubofski.  Elizabeth R. Constable appeared for the State of Wisconsin. State gives plea agreement, 16CM132 ct 1 plea, ct 2 DRI, 16CM65 plea to charge, withheld sentence 12 months probation concurrent, costs, DNA Surcharge, DNA Sample, AODA and follow with treatment recommendation, Absolute Sobriety, Counseling deemed necessary, Maintain fulltime employment or schooling unless provides proof of SDI.  Atty Grubofski and defendant agrees with plea agreement. Plea questionnaire and waiver of rights filed.  Def. understands charges and penalties. 16CM132 Ct 1 D.C., no contest plea, 16CM65 Poss of Controlled Substance, no contest plea.  Court grants &  DRI Ct 2 in 16CM132.  Def. advised of constitutional rights & J.T. rights. Def. understand elements.  Atty Grubofski is satisfied.  Court finds pleas are freely & voluntarily given.  Factual basis. Court finds factual basis, accepts pleas and finds def. Guilty to 16CM132 Ct 1 D.C., & 16CM65 Poss of Controlled Substance.  State request court to accept joint recommendation.  16CM65 2 days credit, 16CM132 3 days credit. Atty Grubofski gives sentencing recommendation. Def. has nothing to say.  Court accepts joint recommendation and orders on 16CM132 ct 1 withheld sentence 12 months probation, costs, 200 DNA Surcharge, DNA Sample unless already provided, State has proof already completed for DNA, Court will order DNA unless already provided,  AODA and follow with treatment recommendation, Maintain Absolute Sobriety, Counseling deemed necessary by agent, Maintain fulltime employment or schooling or combination of 35 hours a week unless provides proof of disability from medical doctor to probation officer.   16CM132 3 days credit if revoked. 16CM65 ct 1 withheld sentence 12 months probation concurrent to 16CM132 costs, 200 DNA Surcharge, Same conditions. 16CM65 2 days credit if revoked. Def. advised of postconviction rights.  If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered, without further order of the court, against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.

Defendant Jeremy J. Gasser in court with attorney Gavin Grubofski.  Galen Bayne-Allison appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court calls  16CM65 & 16FO47 @ 10:00 am. Officer Brady Goeks, City of Antigo Police Department, duly sworn on oath, testifies.  Atty Grubofski request witness be sequestered.  Court orders. Recess @ 10:16 am.  Reconvene @ 10:20 am. State has got his lap top to review video.  Atty Grubofski doesn't have to review video. Officer reviews Statement. Officer Kyle Rustick, City of Antigo Police Department, duly sworn on oath, testifies.  State rest.  Court questions parties.  Court would like briefs filed and than ruling.  Recess @ 10:38 am.  Reconvene @ 10:40 am.  Atty Grubofski agree that statement are suppressed.  State agrees.  Court grants motion to suppress statement and will deny motion for Illegal Search.  Status conference scheduled for August 22, 2016 at 03:30 pm.
